                "name": "Michael Manazaneta",
                "href": "/profile/Michael-Manazaneta"
            },
            "answer_text": "Of course. Life needs a new iteration with new abilities and it can't have the used up iteration using up the new iterations resources. For example. There are some organisms that appear to live forever. Clearly life has tried that route, and deemed it to be insufficient for some(most) organisms (at this time). Imagine if every full grown elephant who ever lived never died. There wouldn't be any peanuts for any new elephants. It is the same think for computers. Would you want to keep an entire building for an original computer? Or would you rather kill that old giant computer break it into reusable bits, build a house with a pool and have a laptop to use whenever wherever you want? Death is a necessary part of life's progress. What life is trying to achieve is a mystery. ",
